{{BLP sources|date=December 2017}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Russel E. Caflisch | image = Russ Caflisch IPAM.jpg | image_size = | caption = Caflisch in 2012 | nationality = [[United States|American]] | field = [[Applied Mathematics]] | work_institutions = [[New York University]], [[UCLA]], [[Institute for Pure and Applied Mathematics|IPAM]] | doctoral_advisor = [[George C. Papanicolaou|George Papanicolaou]] | doctoral_students = }} '''Russel Caflisch''' is an American mathematician.
== Biography ==
Caflisch is Director of the [[Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences]] at [[New York University]] (NYU), and a Professor in the Mathematics Department. He received his bachelor's degree from Michigan State University in 1975. He earned a master's degree and Ph.D. in Mathematics from the Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences at New York University.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} His dissertation was titled "The Fluid Dynamic Limit and Shocks for a Model Boltzmann Equation." He has also held faculty positions at Stanford and NYU. He has served as PhD advisor for 22 students, with 55 descendants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.ams.org/id.php?id=33190|title=Russel Caflisch - The Mathematics Genealogy Project|website=www.genealogy.ams.org|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> Up until August 2017, Caflisch was the director of the [[Institute for Pure and Applied Mathematics|Institute for Pure & Applied Mathematics (IPAM)]] and a professor in the Mathematics department, where he also held a joint appointment in the department of Materials Science and Engineering. <ref>{{Citation | last = | title = IPAM Directors | url= http://www.ipam.ucla.edu/people/directors/ | accessdate = 2017-01-24}} </ref>
Caflisch was a founding member of [[California NanoSystems Institute]] (CNSI). Caflisch’s expertise includes topics in the field of applied mathematics, including [[partial differential equation]]s, [[fluid dynamics]], [[plasma physics]], [[materials science]], [[Quasi-Monte Carlo method|Monte Carlo methods]], and computational finance.
== Recognition == Caflisch was awarded the [[Hertz Foundation|Hertz Foundation Graduate Fellowship]] in 1975 <ref name=Hertz>{{Citation | last = | title = Hertz Foundation Fellows List | url= https://www.hertzfoundation.org/dx/fellows/fellows.aspx | accessdate =}} </ref> and a [[Sloan Fellowship|Sloan Foundation Research Fellowship]] in 1984. He was named a fellow of the [[Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics]] in 2009, <ref name=SIAM>{{Citation | last = | title = SIAM Fellows List | url= http://fellows.siam.org/index.php?sort=year&value=2009#Russel_E._Caflisch | accessdate = }} </ref> the [[American Mathematical Society]] in 2012, <ref name=AMS>{{Citation | last = | title = AMS Fellows List | url= http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list-institution | accessdate = }} </ref> and the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 2013. <ref>{{Citation | last = | title = American Academy of Arts and Sciences Fellows List | url= http://www.ucla.edu/about/awards-and-honors/faculty/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences | accessdate = }} </ref> He gave an Invited Lecture at the 2006 [[International Congress of Mathematicians]].{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}
